ning into a unified metaphor such as a Christmas tree, a menorah, or the American flag. These symbols allow children and adults to co-opt the meaning of symbols in flexible and age-relevant ways, all while the symbols are still treasured and shared in common.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aFamilieszUnited States. 0aHolidaysxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aSymbolismzUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aShweder, Richard A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311065352640uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/9781978802018zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781978802018423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781978802018.jpg  a978-3-11-065352-6  Rutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK